'''David Peter Rock''' (born 8 April 1945) is a [[Latin America]]nist historian, who specializes in the [[history of Argentina]]. He is a professor at the Department of History at the University of California Santa Barbara.
He was born in Blackburn, Lancashire, England and taught briefly in Burnley before studying at [[St John's College, Cambridge]], where he was awarded a Ph.D in 1971. He worked as a Research Officer at the [[Institute of Latin American Studies]] in London from 1970 to 1974. He moved to the U.S. to teach at the University of California in Santa Barbara, where he was promoted to Professor in 1978. <ref> {{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing, Volume 1|first=Kelly|last=Boyd|page=1000}} </ref> He married Rosalind Farrar in 1968, with whom he had two sons.
He has been described as a "leading scholar in the field" of 19th-century [[Argentine political history]].<ref>{{citation |last=Rock |first=David |title=Review of '' State Building and Political Movements in Argentina, 1860–1916'' |journal=The American Historical Review |volume=108 |issue=3 |date=June 2003 |url=http://www.historycooperative.org/cgi-bin/justtop.cgi?act=justtop&url=http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/108.3/br_106.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829061714/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/108.3/br_106.html |archivedate=2007-08-29 |df= |doi=10.1086/ahr/108.3.889 |jstor=10.1086/529703 }}</ref> His history of the country from the sixteenth to the twentieth centuries was adjudged as "a comprehensive, clearly written and intelligent account of the evolution of Argentina which will undoubtedly remain the standard work for years to come."<ref>{{citation|last= Little |first= Walter |title= Review of ''Argentina 1516-1982, from Spanish Colonization to the Falklands War'' |journal= History Today |year= 1987 |url= http://www.historytoday.com/MainArticle.aspx?m=16323&amid=16323 }}</ref> Rock's first book, ''Politics in Argentina, 1890-1930: The Rise and Fall of Radicalism'' on the [[Conference on Latin American History]] Bolton prize for the best book in English. He is professor emeritus of History at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]].
==List of works==
