{{About|the 19th-century art movement|20th century poetic movement|Intimism}}
'''Intimism''' ({{Lang-fr|intimisme}}) was an artistic movement in late 19th-century and early 20th-century that involved the depiction of banal yet highly personal domestic scenes, particularly those within domestic interiors. Intimism was most notably practiced by [[Édouard Vuillard]] and [[Pierre Bonnard]] after the 1899 disbandment of [[Les Nabis|the Nabis]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/Intimism|title=Intimism {{!}} art|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/dcpt/hd_dcpt.htm|title=The Nabis and Decorative Painting|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref>[[File:Breakfast,_Edouard_Vuillard,_1894.jpg|thumb|Breakfast, Edouard Vuillard, 1894]]French art critic [[Camille Mauclair]] defined Intimism as:<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Great French Painters and the Evolution of French Painting from 1830 to the Present Day|last=Mauclair|first=Camille|publisher=Duckworth|year=1903|isbn=|location=|pages=122}}</ref> {{Quote|text=a revelation of the soul through the things painted, the magnetic suggestion of what lies behind them through the description of the outer appearance, the intimate meaning of the spectacles of life |sign=|source=}}While the movement is often associated with [[Impressionism]], the Intimists diverged from the Impressionists in their use of exaggerated and expressive colors over those that more accurately portrayed their subject matter.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/269433597|title=The Oxford dictionary of art and artists|others=Chilvers, Ian.|isbn=9780199532940|edition=Fourth edition|location=Oxford|oclc=269433597}}</ref>
